or the sake of a city that needed quiet nights. Between the ward-stakes and the shadowed hedge, between measured counts and murmured promises, the work would be done or not at all, and all debts would be tallied in light and silence. The Luthien ran friendly beyond the grove, but under the leaves it was a river of another kind, one that ran through voices, names, and the places where vows were tied too loosely and slipped.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Meet Erynn Mirrorfall and Jaya Basaltrip at the edge of the Moonless Orchard.\",\n        \"Collect night-sap from marked quince and smoky plum trees without stepping into full shade.\",\n        \"Assist Jaya in mixing the resin-lacquer and test it on lantern panes.\",\n        \"Evade Night Orchard watchers and respect the Order’s boundary conditions.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Erynn Mirrorfall\", \"lines\": \"Light can be shaped like a hymn and held like a hand, and I have spent half my life learning which lead-lines make it gentler and which edges make it cruel. The city is tired, Jaryn, and the Shard has been singing louder of late, louder than my panes can soften without help, as if our nights have become a bell the size of a river. This lacquer is not a gag for the song nor a chain for the light; it is a shawl to wrap around a fevered child until the heat passes and real rest is possible again. I have studied the old recipes, the drafts that were hidden after the Nightfall edicts, and they all whispered the same thing: ‘Take the sap at the border, under eyes that do not blink and before night truly opens its mouth.’ I know the risk, and I do not ask lightly, but I ask you because you carry the river’s codes in your bones and because I see the way you listen before you act, the way a pilot waits for the next chord of the current before setting the oar.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jaya Basaltrip\", \"lines\": \"The sap is temperamental and storied, like a singer who remembers every hall that ever held her voice and judges you on the acoustics of your soul. It remembers promises made in a whisper and it sulks if you lie, and it does not like to be taken past the first bead of true night, when the grove’s breath deepens and words begin to echo with their own shadows. We’ll mix it at the boundary so the night doesn’t press its thumb through our sums, because even a small smear of dream on the figures will pull the varnish toward sorrow instead of solace. I will count in primes and pause on breaths that match the Shard’s hum, and when I say stop, you stop, even if the tree croons your name like the one person whose forgiveness you keep pretending you don’t need. We will carry copper ward-tiles to ground the math, we will keep to the sun-touched roots, and we will not let the grove talk us into thinking we have more time than we do, because direction is a creature here and it enjoys slipping its leash.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lysa Shardhands\", \"lines\": \"You will hear me say I did not see you cross that last white thread of dust on the rootline, and that will be the end of it so long as the work is done before true night and no bark is cut deeper than a single tear-drop of sap. The Order’s edicts are not curios in a case, they are braces that keep a cracked wall standing, and I have pledged to keep the wall from falling even if it means letting a craftsman slip through a door that should be locked for another hour. Bring your tiles and bind your oaths to them, and if you must speak a promise to the sap, make it a truth that will not sour when the dawn admits how little romance there is in exhaustion. Know this too: if I see Night Orchard gardeners pruning more than rumor out here, my patience ends like a rope under sudden strain, and I will call wardens to this shade even if the Shard itself sings me deaf. I look the other way because I trust the shape of your intent, Jaryn Chainwake, but trust is a pane that can spider with one sharp tap, and I have seen too many spiderwebs in the courts this year.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Iven Shadequinch\", \"lines\": \"You step close to a hedge we have tended with black-sap and patience and, like all careful gardeners, we notice a new hand reaching for fruit at the fence. We do not sell death and we do not tax kindness, but we prune threats, and a clumsy harvest can make a city dream itself into a ditch from which it will wake with broken teeth. Take only from the trees we have marked with a twist of char on the bark, and leave a leaf-fold promise beneath each cut, a small tithe of word to pay for the bruise you’ve asked the tree to wear. We have no quarrel with easing sleep, but understand that the Orchard itself remembers debts, and if you carry more than your share, it will follow you like a rumor until it finds a place to root in your life. Speak your purpose plain at the root-line, and if you mean to chase a memory through our shade, do not expect the path to walk straight for you twice in one night, because even kindness grows wild when unpruned.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jaryn Chainwake\", \"lines\": \"The Orchard took a piece of me once and I have worn the hole like a badge I don’t show, a neat absence that my fingers still map when storms lean against the city and old knots pull in the wood. If I am given the chance to patch it, I won’t grab like a thief or bargain like a counting-hall clerk; I will ask, and if the trees answer, I will take what is offered and no more, and I will leave thanks folded under the skin of the root. I will walk the hem as pilots walk a floodline, with a hand on the chain and an ear for the bell, and I will keep to light where light keeps to me, because I have seen what happens when a man thinks he can outsmart a river that is older than his family’s name. If a shadow leans close and calls me by a name I can’t quite feel, I will set my feet in Jaya’s counts and anchor my breath to the Shard’s low note, and let